title: For Sale:  SIG 556 SWAT Rifle with Swiss bayonet, Magpul 6 position collapsable folding stock, flashligh grip
postcontent:
Lightly used, ~500 rounds, rock solid SIG 556 SWAT rifle with full length quad rails, Swiss bayonet, flashlight fore grip (flashlight not included in the grip), flat top with built in emergency back up iron sights.
Unlike an AR, this Magpul 6 position stock folds and can be shot easily in the folded position. 2-stage trigger, 1 in 7 twist rate barrel, flash hider with square quick attach treads for suppressor, bayonet lug with bayonet and sheath included. The rifle DOES accept standard AR 15/ M16 magazines and 1 black Magpul Gen 3 is provided (can substitute a Gen2 if you want). Also included is the factory hard side plastic case.
This is not the current production rifle and can be hard to find. Below is the description from Sig's website.

http://www.sigsauer.com/CatalogProductDetails/sig556-swat.aspx

SIG556® SWAT Like the SIG556, the SIG556 SWAT features the same high-performance two position adjustable gas piston operating rod system engineered by SIG’s sister company Swiss Arms and marries it to a trigger housing that not only cuts the rifle’s weight by a pound but is designed to accept standard AR magazines. The SIG556 SWAT features a 16” military grade cold hammer forged barrel, chambered in 5.56mm NATO, with a twist rate of 1 in 7”. The high performance flash suppressor provides enhanced flash reduction and features an ACME type thread for compatibility with select industry sound suppression devices. The flash suppressor retains a standard .5 x 28 TPI thread pattern, ensuring compatibility with after-market accessories. The vented tactical quad rail forearm is machined from aircraft grade aluminum alloy and hard coat anodized for durability. The quad rail features four integrated steel Picatinny rails for mounting a wide range of accessories. The Picatinny rail equipped receiver is made of high strength carbon steel with a durable wear-resistant Nitron® finish. The rifle comes standard with the flip up combat front and rear sight system. The trigger housing is machined from an aircraft grade aluminum alloy forging with a hard-coat anodized finish designed to survive extreme conditions. The rifle comes equipped with a smooth two-stage trigger, ambidextrous safety and is designed to accept standard AR magazines. A 30-round magazine is supplied with each rifle. The rifle features the MAGPUL CTR Carbine Buttstock. This buttstock is adjustable for length of pull and features a unique locking mechanism that friction locks the stock to the receiver extension for zero movement. The ergonomically designed pistol grip features an integrated storage compartment. The rifle also includes the Grip-Light vertical forend grip which features a removable tactical LED flashlight and mounts directly to the quad rail forends. Select versions feature a folding stock with the ability to collapse, providing the best of both worlds.

Note: Images shown with optional sling swivels, and second magazine not included.

SIG 556 Rifle Wins NRA Tactical Gun of the Year

Few semi-automatic rifles have captured the imagination of the shooting public like the SG 550 series. For years this legendary Swiss-made rifle has been restricted to law enforcement and military sales, where it has acquired a reputation for reliability, durability and accuracy. Now, SIG Sauer has developed a U.S. made version called the SIG 556 ... .” So stated Shooting Editor Glenn Gilbert in “Like a Swiss Watch” (December 2007, p. 46).

Both 556 SWAT and full-length versions feature the quality shooters have come to expect from SIG, including steel Picatinny rails fixed to the tops of their receivers and military-grade cold-hammer-forged barrels. But these are fully updated designs. Significant changes have been made to the lower receiver and the stock. The cast aluminum lower receiver retains the ambidextrous safety lever of the original 550, but the magazine well has been modified to take commercial and surplus AR-15/M16-style magazines. Further, given the crisp break and limited overtravel of its trigger, the SIG 556’s accuracy was commendable.

“The bottom line, simply stated,” wrote Gilbert, “is that the SIG 556 is an exceptionally accurate and reliable semi-automatic rifle whose performance is more than enough to justify its existence.” That shared sentiment among staffers resulted in the SIG Sauer 556 being named the first-ever American Rifleman Tactical Gun of the Year.

title: For Sale:  Rare and Collectible. 1861 Navy Arms Colt Civil War Commemorative Revolver
postcontent:
HONORING THE 150th ANNIVERSARY OF THE WAR BETWEEN THE STATES.
The Legendary Model 1851 Navy Revolver

One of the most popular sidearms of its day, the legendary Colt 1851 was coveted equally by Northern and Southern soldiers. Time and again, Samuel Colt’s masterpiece proved itself in battle and earned its rightful place as a true American icon. There was little debate when it came to selecting this model as the perfect handgun to commemorate one of the most defining events in American history.

With its 7½-inch octagonal barrel and sleek frame, the Model 1851 Navy remains one of the most sought after and beloved firearms of all time. Each Civil War firearm available in the edition is a meticulously-detailed recreation of the legendary Colt 1851 Navy Revolver, created by the incomparable artisans of A. Uberti. For decades, their craftsmen have combined modern high-grade materials with time-honored methods of finishing to create exquisite, working reproductions of history’s greatest firearms.

Craftsmen decorate each Tribute in stunning 24-karat gold over blued steel, handsomely capturing this momentous occasion.
The left side of the barrel of this Civil War firearm features a 24-karat gold decorated banner, identifying the revolver as the “American Civil War 150th Anniversary Tribute.” Also featured on the left side of the Tribute are the crossed flags of the Union and Confederate forces. Complementing the overall design are lustrously, hand-polished walnut grips.

The right side of the barrel of this Civil War firearm features a famous phrase used by Abraham Lincoln during an 1858 speech “A House Divided Against Itself Cannot Stand.” Lincoln borrowed this axiom from the Bible as a warning about the mounting tensions between the Northern and Southern states. After his election to the presidency, Lincoln continued to cut through the differences that divided our nation and to remind us of what was necessary to restore and repair the broken union. Both sides of the 24-karat gold decorated frame feature a banner with the dates of the Civil War, “1861-1865.”
The centerpiece of the Civil War firearm is the lavishly illustrated cylinder, featured in 24-karat gold and meticulously decorated with an epic scene depicting a clash between Union and Confederate soldiers. From flags to uniforms to facial expressions, no detail has been overlooked in this breathtaking scene, reminiscent of the carnage during the Battle of Antietam. The September 17, 1862 showdown between the Northern forces of General George McClellan and the Southern soldiers under General Robert E. Lee was the bloodiest single-day battle of the war.
In order to display and protect your Civil War Sesquicentennial Tribute Revolver, it is housed in a luxuriously lined display case, including an engraved brass identification plaque and replica Union and Confederate buckles. One of a limited edition. #A85771 This item is #77 of only 1865 made.

Built in 1931 at the Brno plant in Czech, this is a 98 Mauser for the Persian Army.  Silky smooth bolt action. Short overall length, bent bolt implies it was likely used in the cavalry division. All markings are in Arabic and in good shape.  The stock has the dings that you would expect from a 80+ year old rifle.  

*********************************************
I also have a Persian bayonet included.  The Persians like edged weapons and as such this bayonet is a short sword. 

*********************************************
What's a gun if you can't find ammo?  I'm also including about 100 rounds of surplus 8mm and 25 rounds of hunting ammo.

Rob Luft 



A little family history of my dad Eugene Luft and his cousins Carl and Harry Luft i remember meeting them as a teenager. 

The wildcat 30 Luft mag. came out in the late 1930s and rifles made for it up until the late 1950s. It is a 300 H&H mag case blown out, shortened and re-necked to give more power and better performance.

 A fairly scarce round, never caught on. Developed by the Luft Bros. Gunsmiths from Spokane, WA. The Luft brothers were gunsmiths in Spokane Washington and worked alot on custom Borchardt rifles in modern cartridges.

The Luft brothers also made a another wildcat, the 333 Express which was very similar to the 333 OKH.All of the old short magnums (Luft, Mashburn, Ackley, O'Neil, Apex, etc) were made from the 300 H&H or 375 H&H since that is all that was available back then. It's not that hard to do but now-a-days you have all the modern brass so why bother? I shoot a 30 Short Ackley Magnum as my HG at 1000 yard NBRSA and I use 300WM brass. The shoulder pushes back without much work and I then trim the extra .010".

 Or if you don't like trimming you could start with 338WM or 7mmRM. The Norma 308M works too if you can locate the brass. All of the different brass has different inside dimensions, and therefore capacity, and you can control the final capacity of your Mashburn brass when selecting the parent case.

 Luft Brothers in Spokane, WA in the early 1950's to mid-60's. The Luft brothers worked on custom Borchardt rifles but chambered for modern cartridges.

title: For Sale:  1911 80% frame+extras
postcontent:
If you do not know what an 80% receiver is, then this listing is not for you.  This is not for the faint of heart either.  If you had a tough time with an AR-15 80% receiver, this 80% 1911 may very well be your undoing. 

This is the Ares Armor Rudius 80% 1911 frame.  I purchased it with eager plans of completing it, but alas it is just collecting dust in my possession.
It is brand new and I haven't touched it with a single tool (just a little Frog Lube to prevent my dust collection from rusting it).  

Seeing as I am feeling quite happy with my plan to get rid of some of my things, I will throw in the following as freebies: 
•	1 brand new MEC-GAR magazine for .45 ACP
•	1 slightly used thumb safety for a 1911 (like 20 rounds fired through that 1911 before I took it out. I promise)
•	1 slightly used non adjustable trigger for a 1911 (took it out at the same time as the safety... I'm a monster I know)

Now that I have you fully excited, I bet you are wondering what that dashingly handsome complete 1911 is doing in the pictures?  Well, he is not included in this listing and if I said "sorry" I'd be lying. That is just there to illustrate the size difference and hopefully your eye was drawn to the picatinny rail on the dust cover of the 80% frame that could be yours (very very sexy), also the 80% frame is significantly slimmer since the grips don't attach on top of the frame, they are in fact the frame (grab a towel and clean up your exploded mind off your screen).

Lastly since this is only a paperweight to the untrained eye, let me remind you that this can be raised up into different calibers and not just .45 ACP to make use of the free mag.  You could go wimpy 9mm, a little stronger .40, all American .45, or be a frickin weirdo and make it 10mm.


**The only flaw on the frame is from the manufacture: One of the connecting points in the polymer (where the trigger guard mates with the steel) looks like it may brake off, but that part isn't really important at all, so no worries.** 


If you think my price is too high, I'm just going off what I paid and this is at least in stock with freebies.  Check out the retail cost at the Ares Armor site.


Once again this is merely a paperweight since it is an 80% completed frame.  I will ship it directly to you, no need for an FFL.  God's speed.


FOR US SALE ONLY!!
I will not sell outside the US sorry folks.


Edit** It is from the first production run of the Rudius and is the original gen 1 grip**
